VALUES
(20, 3, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'Go, and come again, and to morrow I will give;', 28, 74, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Go'' and ''Give''', 'עַד (ad, H5704) - until, as far as. This term emphasizes a limit or endpoint. In the context of this verse, it suggests that telling a neighbor to wait implies a postponement that could be unnecessary. The urgency of giving what one has can deepen our understanding of community obligations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5704", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term ''ad''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'Devise not evil against thy neighbour, seeing he dwelleth securely by thee.', 0, 75, 'connection', 'Neighborly Conduct', 'This verse connects closely with Leviticus 19:18, which commands, ''You shall love your neighbor as yourself.'' Both verses emphasize the importance of maintaining harmonious relationships and the moral obligation to treat others with respect and kindness. The notion of ''dwelling securely'' suggests a sense of trust that should not be betrayed, reinforcing the call to love and protect one another.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Leviticus 19:18", "description": "Highlights the command to love one''s neighbor."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'Devise not evil against thy neighbour, seeing he dwelleth securely by thee.', 0, 75, 'theology', 'Ethics of Neighborly Love', 'Many scholars believe this verse encapsulates the ethical principle underpinning many biblical teachings on interpersonal relationships. The idea that one should not ''devise evil'' indicates a proactive stance against malice, reflecting God''s character of love and justice. This aligns with the New Testament command to ''do unto others as you would have them do unto you'' (Matthew 7:12), suggesting a continuity of moral teaching throughout Scripture.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 7:12", "description": "Links to the Golden Rule."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'Devise not evil against thy neighbour, seeing he dwelleth securely by thee.', 0, 75, 'question', 'Reflection on Trust', 'What responsibilities do I have toward my neighbors, especially those who trust me? In what ways can I actively promote peace and security in my community, rather than allowing malice or envy to influence my actions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'Devise not evil against thy neighbour, seeing he dwelleth securely by thee.', 0, 75, 'greek', 'Key Hebrew Terms', 'רָעָה (ra''ah, H7489) - to do evil, harm, or break faith. This word underscores the seriousness of plotting against someone who is vulnerable. The term ''securely'' highlights the trust inherent in relationships, making any act of evil a profound betrayal.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7489", "description": "Hebrew term for ''evil'' or ''harm''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'Strive not with a man without cause,', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Avoiding Unjust Conflict', 'This phrase resonates with James 1:19-20, which advises being quick to hear, slow to speak, and slow to anger. Both passages underscore the importance of resolving conflicts peacefully and thoughtfully. Striving without cause leads to unnecessary strife and hinders relationships, mirroring the wisdom found in Proverbs.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:19-20", "description": "Emphasizes the importance of being slow to anger and thoughtful in communication."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'if he have done thee no harm.', 37, 66, 'theology', 'Call to Righteousness', 'Many scholars believe this passage reflects the biblical principle of loving one''s neighbor as oneself (Leviticus 19:18). The absence of harm is a foundational aspect of righteous living, suggesting that believers are called to pursue peace and avoid conflict unless there is just cause. This principle is central to Christian ethics.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Leviticus 19:18", "description": "Highlights the command to love one''s neighbor, foundational to Christian ethics."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'Strive not with a man without cause,', 0, 36, 'question', 'Understanding Just Conflict', 'What criteria do you use to determine if a conflict is just or unjust? Reflect on how this verse guides your interactions with others, especially in resolving disputes. How can you apply this wisdom in your relationships today?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'Envy thou not the oppressor, and choose none of his ways.', 0, 57, 'connection', 'Oppression in Scripture', 'This verse resonates with Psalm 37:1-2, which admonishes believers not to fret over evildoers or envy those who do wrong. Both passages emphasize the futility of desiring the success of the wicked, urging the faithful to trust in God’s justice and timing. Such connections underscore a consistent biblical theme of reliance on divine providence rather than human schemes.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 37:1-2", "description": "Encouragement against envy of evildoers."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'Envy thou not the oppressor, and choose none of his ways.', 0, 57, 'theology', 'God''s View on Oppression', 'This passage suggests that envy of the oppressor can lead to moral decline and spiritual compromise. Many scholars believe it reflects the larger biblical teaching on social justice and righteousness, warning against the allure of worldly power and success that often comes at the expense of others. The righteous are called to uphold integrity rather than emulate the wicked.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs Commentary by Charles Bridges", "description": "Insights on righteousness versus oppression."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'Envy thou not the oppressor, and choose none of his ways.', 0, 57, 'question', 'Reflection on Envy', 'In what ways might we be tempted to envy those who gain success through unjust means? How does recognizing God''s ultimate justice help us resist this temptation and choose a path of righteousness in our daily lives?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'Envy thou not the oppressor, and choose none of his ways.', 0, 57, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Envy''', 'עָוֶל (ʿāvel, H5753) - wrong, injustice, cruelty. This Hebrew term emphasizes the moral implications of oppression and wrongdoing, highlighting that envy towards oppressors reflects a deeper issue of valuing injustice over righteousness. This connection enhances our understanding of the call to resist such attitudes.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5753", "description": "Strong''s number for ''wrong'' or ''injustice.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'For the froward is abomination to the Lord:', 0, 43, 'connection', 'Frowardness in Scripture', 'This phrase echoes Proverbs 11:20, which states, ''They that are of a froward heart are abomination to the Lord.'' Both verses highlight the seriousness with which God views frowardness, suggesting a consistent biblical theme regarding moral integrity. Understanding this connection reinforces the importance of aligning one’s actions with God’s standards to avoid His displeasure.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 11:20", "description": "Related verse emphasizing God''s view on frowardness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'but his secret is with the righteous.', 44, 81, 'theology', 'God''s Revelation to the Righteous', 'This passage suggests that God''s intimate knowledge and secrets are reserved for the righteous. Many scholars believe this reflects the relational aspect of faith, where righteousness opens the door to deeper understanding of God''s will and character. This aligns with James 4:8, which emphasizes that drawing near to God leads to His drawing near to us.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 4:8", "description": "Emphasizes the relationship between righteousness and closeness to God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'For the froward is abomination to the Lord:', 0, 43, 'question', 'Understanding Frowardness', 'What does it mean to be froward in today''s context, and how can we identify frowardness in our own lives? Reflecting on this can help us align our behavior more closely with God''s standards, seeking to embody integrity and wisdom in our daily actions.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'but his secret is with the righteous.', 44, 81, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Secret''', 'סוֹד (sod, H5475) - secret, confidential conversation. This term suggests a deep level of intimacy and trust. In biblical context, it often refers to divine counsel or knowledge imparted to those who are in a right relationship with God, indicating that the righteous have access to insights that are not available to the wicked.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5475", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for secret."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'The curse of the Lord is in the house of the wicked:', 0, 52, 'connection', 'Divine Judgment Theme', 'This phrase parallels Romans 1:18, which discusses the wrath of God revealed against unrighteousness. Both verses highlight God''s judgment on wickedness, emphasizing that living outside His will invites consequences. Understanding this connection reinforces the notion that God''s character inherently opposes evil, leading to divine repercussions for the wicked.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 1:18", "description": "Discusses God''s wrath against unrighteousness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'but he blesseth the habitation of the just.', 53, 96, 'theology', 'Blessings of Righteousness', 'This passage suggests that God''s favor rests upon those who live justly and righteously. Many scholars believe this reflects a broader biblical theme found in the Beatitudes (Matthew 5:3-12), where blessings are pronounced upon the meek, merciful, and pure in heart. This connection affirms the theological principle that a life aligned with God''s will receives His blessings.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 5:3-12", "description": "Jesus'' teachings on blessings for the righteous."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'The curse of the Lord is in the house of the wicked:', 0, 52, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Curses', 'What does it mean for a household to be under the curse of the Lord? How can this understanding of divine judgment affect our daily choices and the environment we cultivate in our homes?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'but he blesseth the habitation of the just.', 53, 96, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''Bless'' in Hebrew', 'בָּרַךְ (barak, H1288) - to bless, to kneel. This term conveys a sense of divine favor and gratitude, suggesting that God''s blessings are not merely material but encompass spiritual well-being and peace.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1288", "description": "Hebrew term for ''bless'' with significance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 34, 34, 'kjv', 'Surely he scorneth the scorners:', 0, 32, 'connection', 'Scorn and Divine Judgment', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 1:1, which warns against walking in the counsel of the wicked, highlighting the same theme of divine disfavor towards those who scorn. Additionally, James 4:6 states that ''God resists the proud, but gives grace to the humble,'' reinforcing the notion that God actively opposes those who exhibit scornful behavior. Understanding these connections illustrates a consistent biblical principle regarding God''s stance against arrogance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 1:1", "description": "Highlights divine disfavor towards the wicked."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 4:6", "description": "Reinforces God''s opposition to pride and scorn."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 34, 34, 'kjv', 'but he giveth grace unto the lowly.', 33, 68, 'theology', 'Grace for the Humble', 'This passage suggests a profound theological truth regarding God''s grace. Many scholars believe that humility is a prerequisite for receiving God''s grace, as seen throughout Scripture. This aligns with the beatitudes in Matthew 5, where the poor in spirit are blessed. The concept of grace being given to the lowly emphasizes God''s preferential treatment towards those who recognize their need for Him.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 5:3", "description": "Illustrates the blessedness of the humble."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 34, 34, 'kjv', 'Surely he scorneth the scorners:', 0, 32, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Scorn', 'What does it reveal about God''s character that He actively scorns those who scorn others? How does this understanding affect our attitudes towards pride and mockery in our own lives?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 34, 34, 'kjv', 'but he giveth grace unto the lowly.', 33, 68, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Grace''', 'χάρις (charis, G5485) - grace, favor, kindness. This term encompasses not just unmerited favor but also the empowering presence of God in the life of the believer. The use of ''charis'' here emphasizes that grace is a divine gift bestowed upon those who are humble and lowly, highlighting the relational aspect of grace in the believer''s experience.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5485", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek word for grace."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 35, 35, 'kjv', 'The wise shall inherit glory', 0, 28, 'connection', 'Inheriting Glory', 'This phrase echoes the themes found in Daniel 12:3, where the wise are said to shine like the stars. Both passages emphasize the eternal reward for wisdom and righteousness. The connection highlights the biblical principle that wisdom leads to divine favor and ultimate glory, reinforcing the value of living a life aligned with God''s teachings.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Daniel 12:3", "description": "The wise will shine in eternity."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 35, 35, 'kjv', 'but shame shall be the promotion of fools', 30, 71, 'theology', 'Consequences of Foolishness', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects a key aspect of biblical wisdom literature: the stark contrast between wisdom and folly. The promotion of shame for fools suggests that their choices lead to humiliation and downfall, which aligns with the overarching theme of Proverbs emphasizing moral integrity. This underscores the theological belief that God’s justice prevails in the moral order of the universe.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 3, 35, 35, 'kjv', 'The wise shall inherit glory', 0, 28, 'question', 'What is True Wisdom?', 'What does it mean to be wise in the context of this verse? How can we discern true wisdom from mere knowledge in our daily lives? Reflecting on this may help us understand the qualities that lead to glory and how we can cultivate them in alignment with God’s purpose.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Hear, ye children, the instruction of a father', 0, 46, 'connection', 'Parental Guidance', 'This verse echoes Ephesians 6:1-4, where children are instructed to obey their parents in the Lord. The connection highlights the importance of parental wisdom in spiritual upbringing, suggesting that divine instruction often comes through earthly authority figures. Understanding this relationship reinforces the need for children to value and seek out wisdom from their parents.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ephesians 6:1-4", "description": "Children are called to obey their parents, emphasizing the significance of parental instruction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'the instruction of a father', 19, 46, 'theology', 'Role of Fathers', 'This verse suggests that fathers have a divinely ordained role in imparting wisdom and instruction to their children. Many scholars believe that this reflects the broader biblical principle of familial responsibility, where the father is seen as a primary teacher of moral and spiritual truths, a role echoed in the teachings of Proverbs throughout.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the role of fathers in guiding their children''s spiritual education."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'attend to know understanding', 52, 80, 'question', 'Seeking Understanding', 'What does it mean to ''attend to know understanding''? In what ways can we actively pursue wisdom in our daily lives? This prompts reflection on the importance of being intentional about learning and applying the teachings we receive, both from scripture and from those who guide us.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'good doctrine', 15, 28, 'greek', 'Significance of Doctrine', 'The term ''doctrine'' translates from the Hebrew מוּסָר (musar, H4148), which means instruction or discipline. This highlights the importance of not just knowledge, but the transformative aspect of adhering to God''s teachings. In this context, ''good doctrine'' signifies teachings that lead to a righteous life.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4148", "description": "Strong''s number for Hebrew term related to instruction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'forsake ye not my law', 30, 51, 'connection', 'Importance of Law', 'This phrase connects with Deuteronomy 6:17, which states, ''Ye shall diligently keep the commandments of the Lord your God.'' Both verses emphasize the necessity of adhering to divine law as a means to live righteously. This connection reinforces the idea that God''s law is a foundation for moral living.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 6:17", "description": "Highlights the importance of keeping God''s commandments."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'I give you good doctrine', 4, 28, 'theology', 'Role of Divine Instruction', 'This verse suggests that divine instruction is a gift meant for guidance and growth. Many scholars believe that the ''good doctrine'' refers to the ethical and moral teachings that lead to a fulfilling life in alignment with God''s will. This underscores the value of seeking wisdom and adhering to spiritual teachings.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 4:2", "description": "Commentaries emphasize the transformative power of divine teachings."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'forsake ye not my law', 30, 51, 'question', 'Application of God''s Law', 'What does it mean to you personally to ''not forsake'' God''s law in a world that often values autonomy over divine guidance? How can you actively incorporate His teachings into your daily decisions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'For I was my father’s son', 0, 25, 'connection', 'Parental Guidance', 'This phrase resonates with other scriptures emphasizing the importance of parental instruction. For instance, Ephesians 6:1-4 underscores the obligation of children to honor their parents while parents are instructed to nurture their children in the ways of the Lord. This connection highlights the foundational role of family in spiritual education.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ephesians 6:1-4", "description": "Calls for children to obey their parents and for parents to raise their children with godly instruction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'tender and only beloved', 27, 50, 'theology', 'God''s Affection', 'The description of being ''tender and only beloved'' reflects God''s intimate affection for His people. Many scholars believe this highlights the special relationship that God desires with each individual, akin to that of a parent. This theological insight encourages believers to understand their worth and value in the eyes of God.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'my father’s son', 10, 25, 'greek', 'Sonship in Context', 'בֵּן (ben, H1121) - son. This Hebrew term is significant as it denotes not just biological relation but also denotes inheritance and identity. The concept of sonship implies a relationship that carries responsibilities and privileges, making it a profound aspect of familial and divine connection.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1121", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''son.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'my father’s son', 10, 25, 'question', 'Understanding Identity', 'What does it mean to be referred to as ''my father’s son'' in the context of your own relationship with God? How does this identity shape your understanding of your place within the family of faith?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'Let thine heart retain my words:', 37, 69, 'connection', 'Heart and Words Connection', 'This phrase echoes Deuteronomy 6:6, where God commands His people to keep His words in their hearts. The connection emphasizes the importance of internalizing divine teachings, which leads to spiritual vitality. Retaining God''s words in the heart is a recurring theme in Scripture, highlighting the transformative power of His commandments.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 6:6", "description": "God''s command to keep His words in our hearts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'keep my commandments, and live.', 70, 101, 'theology', 'Life Through Obedience', 'This passage suggests that obedience to God''s commandments is integral to spiritual life. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader biblical principle that true life—both spiritual and physical—stems from following God''s will, as seen in John 10:10 where Jesus states He came to give abundant life. The connection reinforces the notion that divine commandments are not burdensome but are pathways to flourishing.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "John 10:10", "description": "Jesus indicates that following Him leads to abundant life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'keep my commandments, and live.', 70, 101, 'question', 'Understanding True Life', 'What does it mean to ''live'' in the context of keeping God''s commandments? Consider how obedience shapes not just our actions, but our very existence and relationship with God. How does this understanding influence your daily choices and spiritual practices?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'He taught me also, and said unto me,', 0, 36, 'greek', 'Teaching and Instruction', 'דָּרַשׁ (darash, H1875) - to seek, inquire, or consult. This term signifies a deep engagement in seeking wisdom. The father''s role in teaching reflects the importance of active instruction in the pursuit of understanding God''s ways, suggesting that wisdom is not merely received but sought after diligently.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1875", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term indicating seeking wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Get wisdom, get understanding:', 0, 30, 'connection', 'Wisdom''s Importance', 'This phrase echoes the theme found in James 1:5, where believers are encouraged to ask God for wisdom. Both passages highlight the pursuit of wisdom as essential for living a righteous life. The wisdom sought in Proverbs is practical and rooted in the fear of the Lord, while James emphasizes divine wisdom that is generously given to those who seek it.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:5", "description": "Encouragement to seek wisdom from God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'forget it not;', 31, 45, 'theology', 'Memory and Discipleship', 'The admonition to ''forget it not'' suggests the importance of memory in discipleship. Many scholars believe that retaining God’s wisdom is foundational for spiritual growth and moral living. This reflects the Jewish tradition of memorizing Scripture, which serves as a guide for ethical behavior and decision-making.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'neither decline from the words of my mouth.', 46, 89, 'question', 'Staying True to God''s Word', 'What are the practical ways in which we might decline from the words of wisdom we receive? Reflecting on this can lead to a deeper understanding of how distractions and societal pressures may lead us away from God''s teachings, prompting us to assess our commitment to living according to His guidance.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Forsake her not, and she shall preserve thee:', 0, 45, 'connection', 'Preservation through Wisdom', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 121:7, which states, ''The LORD shall preserve thee from all evil: he shall preserve thy soul.'' Both verses emphasize the protective nature of wisdom and divine guidance. The connection highlights wisdom not only as a personal asset but also as a spiritual safeguard.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 121:7", "description": "Illustrates God''s preservation of those who seek Him."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'love her, and she shall keep thee.', 46, 80, 'theology', 'The Relationship with Wisdom', 'This passage suggests that loving wisdom is central to receiving its benefits. Many scholars believe that wisdom is personified in Scripture, akin to the relationship believers have with Christ (1 Corinthians 1:30). This reflects the idea that a genuine affection for wisdom leads to spiritual growth and protection.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "1 Corinthians 1:30", "description": "Highlights Christ as our wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Forsake her not, and she shall preserve thee:', 0, 45, 'question', 'Value of Wisdom''s Preservation', 'What does it mean to actively ''forsake'' wisdom in our daily lives? How can we ensure that we are not neglecting the pursuit of wisdom amidst the distractions of the world?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'love her, and she shall keep thee.', 46, 80, 'greek', 'Key Greek Terms', 'ἀγαπάω (agapao, G25) - to love, to cherish. This term reflects a deep, selfless love that transcends mere affection, suggesting that our relationship with wisdom should be one of reverence and commitment.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G25", "description": "Strong''s definition of the word for love used in this context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 4, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Wisdom is the principal thing; therefore get wisdom:', 0, 52, 'connection', 'Wisdom''s Importance', 'This phrase connects to James 1:5, where believers are encouraged to ask God for wisdom, affirming its essential role in the Christian life. Additionally, Proverbs 3:13 emphasizes the value of finding wisdom, illustrating that wisdom is foundational for a successful and fulfilling life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:5", "description": "Encouragement to seek wisdom from God."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 3:13", "description": "Affirmation of the value of wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');